    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Nahua symbol having a curl shape or spiral shape, representing the cross-section of a Strombus gigas or Turbinella angulata conch shell. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000104499/Pillsbury, Potts, Richter, Golden Kingdoms: Luxury Arts in the Ancient Americas (2017)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Símbolo nahua que tiene una forma de rizo o espiral, representando la sección transversal de una concha de Strombus gigas o Turbinella angulata.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109721/GRI, FloCo terminology (2019-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Cimboloh nahuatl tlen neci quence huihhuicoltic zo quence yahyahualtic, quimanextia ce achi tlen monehpanohtoc ipan ce chalolo zo ceyoc tlamantli chalolo.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Eastern Huasteca Nahuatl</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
